Day 5 — Lists, Tuples, Dicts, Sets

Today is the workhorse day for Python data structures. These four show up in every program you write from here on, and the choice between them is rarely arbitrary — each one encodes a different intent about your data. By the end of today you should be able to look at a problem and instantly know which container fits.

We'll do them in order: lists → tuples → dicts → sets. Same loop as always — I explain, you predict, you type, you run, we discuss the mismatches.

Concept 1: Lists — from first principles

A list is an ordered, mutable sequence of objects. Let's unpack each word, because each one is doing real work.
Ordered: the items have positions. The thing you put in first stays first (until you move it). Position matters — [1, 2, 3] is not the same list as [3, 2, 1]. This means you can index into them: my_list[0] gives you the first item.
Mutable: you can change the list in place after creating it. Add items, remove items, replace items — the list object itself stays the same object (same identity, same id()), but its contents change. This is the crucial property that connects back to Day 2's reference model. Remember the aliasing trap? Lists are the classic example. If two names point to the same list and you mutate through one name, the other name sees the change — because there's only one list.

Sequence of objects: a list doesn't store values, it stores references to objects. This is why a list can hold mixed types: [1, "hello", 3.14, True] is perfectly legal. Each slot just holds a pointer to whatever object lives there. (In practice you almost always want homogeneous lists — same type throughout — because that's what most algorithms and type hints expect. But Python doesn't enforce it.)

Creating lists
Two ways:

empty = []                    # literal, empty
nums = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]        # literal, with items
also_empty = list()           # constructor, empty
from_string = list("hello")   # constructor from iterable → ['h', 'e', 'l', 'l', 'o']

Indexing and slicing

Indices start at 0. Negative indices count from the end: -1 is the last item, -2 is second-to-last.
nums = [10, 20, 30, 40, 50]
nums[0]    # 10
nums[-1]   # 50
nums[2]    # 30

Slicing takes a range: nums[start:stop]. The start is inclusive, the stop is exclusive. This off-by-one rule is universal in Python — get it into muscle memory now.

nums[1:4]    # [20, 30, 40]    — indices 1, 2, 3
nums[:3]     # [10, 20, 30]    — from start to index 3 (excl.)
nums[2:]     # [30, 40, 50]    — from index 2 to end
nums[:]      # [10, 20, 30, 40, 50]  — full copy

That last one — nums[:] — is important. It creates a new list with the same contents. This is one of the standard ways to copy a list and break the aliasing trap.
Mutation — the methods that change the list in place

Mutation — the methods that change the list in place
These are the ones to know cold:

Method        What it does

lst.append(x)       adds x to the end
lst.extend(iter)    adds all items from iter to the end
lst.insert(i, x)    inserts x at index i, shifting later items right
lst.pop()           removes and returns the last item
lst.pop(i)          removes and returns the item at index i
lst.remove(x)       removes the first occurrence of x (by value)
lst.sort()          sorts the list in place
lst.reverse()       reverses the list in place

Critical detail: all of these return None (except pop, which returns the popped item). This is the same None-return pattern as print(). So result = my_list.sort() is a bug — result will be None, and your list got sorted as a side effect.
If you want a sorted copy without mutating the original, use the built-in function sorted(my_list) instead — that returns a new list.
